                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 6.615,
                                "byte_start": 105472,
                                "byte_stop": 132012,
                                "text": "In case 08964 Bilski versus Kappos, Justice Kennedy has the opinion of the Court."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 6.615,
                        "stop": 303.303,
                        "byte_start": 132012,
                        "byte_stop": 1318703,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15113,
                            "name": "Anthony M. Kennedy",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/anthony_m_kennedy",
                            "last_name": "Kennedy",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2757,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 572162400,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Ronald Reagan",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2757"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32679,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 47100,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/anthony_kennedy_1_3.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 10147,
                            "identifier": "anthony_m_kennedy"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 6.615,
                                "stop": 17.255,
                                "byte_start": 132012,
                                "byte_stop": 174540,
                                "text": "The petitioner seek to patent a series of steps that instruct buyers and sellers how to protect against the risk of price changes and especially in the energy markets."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 17.255,
                                "stop": 42.348,
                                "byte_start": 174540,
                                "byte_stop": 274954,
                                "text": "Using petitioner\u0027s method, for example a large energy company can protect against the risk that a drastic change in weather will lead to a decrease in demand for its product, the utility company might worry that if there is particularly mild winter its revenues would be insufficient to cover its long-term supply contracts and so it may seek ways in which to hedge against that risk."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 42.348,
                                "stop": 50.045,
                                "byte_start": 274954,
                                "byte_stop": 305674,
                                "text": "United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit sitting en banc held petitioner\u0027s application was not eligible for patent protection."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 50.045,
                                "stop": 62.935,
                                "byte_start": 305674,
                                "byte_stop": 357292,
                                "text": "The Court of Appeals explained that the claimed invention at issue was not patentable because it was not tied to a particular machine nor did it -- and it did not transform a particular article into a different state or thing."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 62.935,
                                "stop": 74.561,
                                "byte_start": 357292,
                                "byte_stop": 403790,
                                "text": "In the Court of Appeals, the case produced five different opinions, including three dissents and students of the patent law will be well advised to read these scholarly opinions from the Court of Appeals."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 74.561,
                                "stop": 89.421,
                                "byte_start": 403790,
                                "byte_stop": 463245,
                                "text": "Section 101 of the Patent Act specifies four independent categories of inventions or discoveries that are eligible for protection. Processes, machines, manufactures and compositions of matter."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 89.421,
                                "stop": 94.135,
                                "byte_start": 463245,
                                "byte_stop": 482053,
                                "text": "This case concerns the patentability of a process."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 94.135,
                                "stop": 104.553,
                                "byte_start": 482053,
                                "byte_stop": 523745,
                                "text": "The act defines this term as process, art or method that includes a new use of a known process, machine, manufacture, composition of matter or material."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 104.553,
                                "stop": 121.268,
                                "byte_start": 523745,
                                "byte_stop": 590618,
                                "text": "In addition the Court\u0027s precedents provide three specific exceptions to Section 101 broad patent eligibility principles and those exceptions are for the laws of nature, physical phenomena and abstract ideas."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 121.268,
                                "stop": 130.761,
                                "byte_start": 590618,
                                "byte_stop": 628548,
                                "text": "The Court today rejects the Court of Appeals rule that the machine or transformation test is the exclusive test for whether a process is patentable."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 130.761,
                                "stop": 138.783,
                                "byte_start": 628548,
                                "byte_stop": 660626,
                                "text": "This Court is more than once cautioned that court should not read into the patent laws, limitations and conditions which the Legislature has not expressed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 138.783,
                                "stop": 150.944,
                                "byte_start": 660626,
                                "byte_stop": 709319,
                                "text": "The Court is unaware of any ordinary, contemporary or common meaning of the definitional terms process or the method that would require these terms be tied to a machine or to transform an article."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 150.944,
                                "stop": 164.637,
                                "byte_start": 709319,
                                "byte_stop": 764071,
                                "text": "This Court\u0027s precedents establish that the machine or transformation test is a useful and important clue, but not the exclusive test for determining whether some claimed inventions are processes."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 164.637,
                                "stop": 175.075,
                                "byte_start": 764071,
                                "byte_stop": 805867,
                                "text": "For a similar reason, Section 101 precludes a broad contention that the term process categorically excludes business method patents."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 175.075,
                                "stop": 184.784,
                                "byte_start": 805867,
                                "byte_stop": 844633,
                                "text": "The Court is unaware of any argument that the ordinary meaning of the term method which is within the statutory definition of process, would exclude business methods."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 184.784,
                                "stop": 202.78,
                                "byte_start": 844633,
                                "byte_stop": 916626,
                                "text": "The argument that business methods are categorically outside of Section 101 scope is further undermined by the fact that Section 273 explicitly contemplates the existence of at least some business method patents by creating a special defense applicable only to those patents."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 202.78,
                                "stop": 208.583,
                                "byte_start": 916626,
                                "byte_stop": 939823,
                                "text": "The conclusion that business method patents are always unpatentable would render Section 273 meaningless."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 208.583,
                                "stop": 224.898,
                                "byte_start": 939823,
                                "byte_stop": 1005129,
                                "text": "Rather than adopting categorical rules that might have unforeseen impacts, the Court today resolves this case narrowly on the basis of this Court\u0027s earlier decisions in three cases and the opinion refers to those cases as Benson and Fluke and Dyer."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 224.898,
                                "stop": 234.381,
                                "byte_start": 1005129,
                                "byte_stop": 1043059,
                                "text": "These precedents establish that the claims the petitioners make in this case are not patentable processes, because they attempt to patent abstract ideas."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 234.381,
                                "stop": 241.584,
                                "byte_start": 1043059,
                                "byte_stop": 1071898,
                                "text": "Today all members of the Court agree that the patent application at issue claims an abstract idea and so is not patentable."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 241.584,
                                "stop": 252.386,
                                "byte_start": 1071898,
                                "byte_stop": 1115052,
                                "text": "As Judge Ryder at the Court of Appeals said hedging is a fundamental economic practice long prevalent in our system of commerce and taught in any introductory finance class."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 252.386,
                                "stop": 259.827,
                                "byte_start": 1115052,
                                "byte_stop": 1144832,
                                "text": "Today the Court once again declines to impose limitations on the Patent Act that are inconsistent with the act\u0027s text."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 259.827,
                                "stop": 265.389,
                                "byte_start": 1144832,
                                "byte_stop": 1167088,
                                "text": "The patent application here can be rejected under precedence on the unpatentability of abstract ideas."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 265.389,
                                "stop": 285.431,
                                "byte_start": 1167088,
                                "byte_stop": 1247232,
                                "text": "Nothing in today\u0027s opinion should be read as endorsing interpretations of the Patent Act the Court of Appeals used in the past and in disapproving an exclusive machine or transformation test we by no means foreclose the Federal Circuit\u0027s development of other limiting criteria that further the purposes of the Patent Act and are not inconsistent with its text."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 285.431,
                                "stop": 288.072,
                                "byte_start": 1247232,
                                "byte_stop": 1257785,
                                "text": "The judgment of the Court of Appeals is affirmed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 288.072,
                                "stop": 294.989,
                                "byte_start": 1257785,
                                "byte_stop": 1285475,
                                "text": "Justice Stevens has filed an opinion concurring in the judgment in which Justices Ginsburg, Breyer and Satomayor join."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 294.989,
                                "stop": 303.303,
                                "byte_start": 1285475,
                                "byte_stop": 1318703,
                                "text": "Justices Breyer -- Justice Breyer has filed an opinion concurring in the judgment in which Justice Scalia joins in part."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 303.303,
                        "stop": 482.612,
                        "byte_start": 1318703,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15060,
                            "name": "John Paul Stevens",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/john_paul_stevens",
                            "last_name": "Stevens",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2704,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 188200800,
                                    "date_end": 1277787600,
                                    "appointing_president": "Gerald Ford",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2704"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32732,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 62101,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/john_paul_stevens.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 12611,
                            "identifier": "john_paul_stevens"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 303.303,
                                "stop": 317.082,
                                "byte_start": 1318703,
                                "byte_stop": 1373874,
                                "text": "As Justice Kennedy has pointed out I have filed a concurring opinion which is an extremely long opinion concurring in the judgment that\u0027s joined by Justice Breyer, Justice Ginsburg and Justice Satomayor."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 317.082,
                                "stop": 326.562,
                                "byte_start": 1373874,
                                "byte_stop": 1411803,
                                "text": "My opinion discusses the question whether business methods are patentable subject matter at some length, but this statement will be brief."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 326.562,
                                "stop": 338.404,
                                "byte_start": 1411803,
                                "byte_stop": 1459137,
                                "text": "Throughout our history the profit incentive has motivated progressive businessmen to device better and better ways to conduct business without any patent protection at all."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 338.404,
                                "stop": 357.169,
                                "byte_start": 1459137,
                                "byte_stop": 1534161,
                                "text": "It is quite clear that neither the patent clause in the Constitution nor early Patent Law in England or America, nor the authors of the statutory provisions defining patentable subject matter ever contemplated that innovative business methods might be patentable."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 357.169,
                                "stop": 386.795,
                                "byte_start": 1534161,
                                "byte_stop": 1652757,
                                "text": "When Congress passed the most recent Patent Act in 1952, it used the term Process to define a category of patentable subject matter, but it was widely understood that in the context of patentable, the term Process does not mean as ordinary speakers might use the term, any series of steps or any way to do anything otherwise the Patent Act would be almost comical."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 386.795,
                                "stop": 393.245,
                                "byte_start": 1652757,
                                "byte_stop": 1678461,
                                "text": "A process for deciding whether to pitch a curve ball or change of pace could be patented."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 393.245,
                                "stop": 408.951,
                                "byte_start": 1678461,
                                "byte_stop": 1741364,
                                "text": "In the late 1990s a Federal Circuit Court of Appeals opinion suggested that any series of steps with a useful, concrete and tangible result may be patented, this included business methods."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 408.951,
                                "stop": 420.028,
                                "byte_start": 1741364,
                                "byte_stop": 1785668,
                                "text": "Congress was surprised by this Circuit Court opinion and it quickly responded with a stopgap measure to limit what could be a significant problem for business community."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 420.028,
                                "stop": 436.637,
                                "byte_start": 1785668,
                                "byte_stop": 1852123,
                                "text": "Congress passed the first Inventor\u0027s Defense Act of 1999 which provides a special defense to claims of patent infringements for methods of doing business, that is this statute that\u0027s referred to as Section 273."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 436.637,
                                "stop": 442.665,
                                "byte_start": 1852123,
                                "byte_stop": 1876156,
                                "text": "Today the Court goes out of its way to state that at least some business methods are patentable."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 442.665,
                                "stop": 455.414,
                                "byte_start": 1876156,
                                "byte_stop": 1927147,
                                "text": "Ironically it relies on the very 1999 act that Congress passed in response to the surprise that business methods might be patentable after all."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 455.414,
                                "stop": 472.716,
                                "byte_start": 1927147,
                                "byte_stop": 1996424,
                                "text": "I think it obvious that Congress would never have an enacted that provision if it had foreseen that this Court would rely on that defensive reaction to a surprise development as a basis for deciding that business methods are in fact patentable subject matter."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 472.716,
                                "stop": 482.612,
                                "byte_start": 1996424,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Accordingly while I concur in the judgment, I strongly disagree with the Court\u0027s timid disposition of this case."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
